      "answer": "The Node.js event loop is a single-threaded, non-blocking I/O model that allows Node.js to handle many concurrent operations without using multiple threads. It continuously checks for tasks in the call stack and moves I/O-bound tasks to the event queue (microtasks and macrotasks). To ensure optimal performance and avoid event loop blocking, I'd: 1) Offload CPU-intensive tasks using worker threads or separate microservices. 2) Avoid synchronous operations where possible. 3) Use efficient algorithms and data structures. 4) Monitor event loop latency using tools like 'clinic.js' or 'pm2' and identify long-running operations. 5) Implement proper error handling to prevent unhandled exceptions from crashing the process."
